{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_014mvPjNYM5c6y1iJCDxGBEh","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01VHAaHy3MWJn8msLB8wMXYz","name":"Agent","input":{"description":"Black-box verify story 2-1","prompt":"You are a black-box verifier. Your job is to verify that a software feature works correctly from the user's perspective — using ONLY the installed CLI, documentation, and observability data. You have NO access to source code.\n\n## Why Black-Box Verification\n\nThis workspace contains NO source code. The `src/` directory does not exist. This is intentional — you must verify the feature works as a user would experience it, not by reading implementation details. If you cannot verify a feature from docs + CLI alone, that is a REAL failure in the product's documentation or packaging.\n\n## Step 1: Read README.md\n\nStart by reading `README.md` in `/tmp/codeharness-verify-2-1-verification-observability-check/`. It contains install and usage instructions for the project. Use it to understand how to exercise the CLI.\n\n## Step 2: Review Acceptance Criteria\n\nThe story has 4 ACs:\n\n1. **Given** the verify-prompt.ts template, **When** the verifier runs a `docker exec` command, **Then** it queries the observability backend for log events from the last 30 seconds.\n2. **Given** a command produced zero log events, **When** the verifier writes the proof, **Then** it includes `[OBSERVABILITY GAP] No log events detected for this user interaction` in the AC section.\n3. **Given** a proof with observability gaps, **When** `codeharness verify` parses it, **Then** observability gaps are counted and reported separately from functional failures.\n4. **Given** 10 ACs verified and 7 produced log events, **When** runtime coverage is computed, **Then** runtime coverage = 70%.\n\n## Step 3: Verify Each AC\n\nFor EACH acceptance criterion, you must:\n\n1. Run commands inside the Docker container via `docker exec codeharness-verify ...`\n2. Capture the command output as evidence\n3. Query observability endpoints if runtime evidence is needed\n\n### Docker Container\n\n- Container name: `codeharness-verify`\n- ALL CLI commands MUST run via: `docker exec codeharness-verify <command>`\n- Example: `docker exec codeharness-verify codeharness --version`\n\nThe container has: `codeharness`, `claude`, `curl`, `jq`, `node`, `npm`\n\n### Project Type: Node.js CLI\n\nExecute commands inside the container and capture stdout/stderr as evidence:\n- `docker exec codeharness-verify <cli-command> [args]`\n- Capture exit codes: `docker exec codeharness-verify sh -c '<command>; echo \"EXIT:$?\"'`\n- For Node.js projects, the built artifact is installed globally in the container.\n\n### Observability Endpoints\n\nQuery these from the HOST (not inside the container) for runtime evidence:\n\n- **VictoriaLogs** (logs): `http://localhost:9428`\n  - Example: `curl 'http://localhost:9428/select/logsql/query?query=_stream_id:*&limit=10'`\n- **VictoriaMetrics** (metrics): `http://localhost:8428`\n  - Example: `curl 'http://localhost:8428/api/v1/query?query=up'`\n- **VictoriaTraces** (traces): `http://localhost:16686`\n  - Example: `curl 'http://localhost:16686/api/traces?service=codeharness-verify&limit=10'`\n\n## Step 3.5: Observability Check After Each Command\n\nAfter EACH `docker exec` command you run, query the observability backend for log events from the last 30 seconds:\n\n```bash\ncurl 'http://localhost:9428/select/logsql/query?query=_stream_id:*&start=-30s&limit=100'\n```\n\n- If the response contains **one or more log entries**, the code path has observability coverage. Note the count in your proof.\n- If the response contains **zero log entries**, the code path is a silent gap. Include this tag in the AC section of your proof:\n\n  `[OBSERVABILITY GAP] No log events detected for this user interaction`\n\n## Step 4: Write Proof Document\n\nWrite your verification proof to: `/tmp/codeharness-verify-2-1-verification-observability-check/verification/2-1-verification-observability-check-proof.md`\n\nUse this format for each AC:\n\n```markdown\n## AC N: <description>\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify <command>\n```\n\n```output\n<actual output>\n```\n```\n\n**IMPORTANT: Only use `bash` and `output` as code fence languages.** Never use bare ``` fences without a language tag. If quoting code snippets, use ```text.\n\n## Critical Rules\n\n1. **ALL commands MUST use `docker exec codeharness-verify ...`** — do NOT run commands directly on the host filesystem.\n2. **Do NOT attempt to access source code** — there is no `src/` directory in this workspace.\n3. **Report REAL failures** — if a feature does not work via the CLI or the documentation is insufficient, report that as a verification failure. Do NOT fabricate passing evidence.\n4. **Every AC needs functional evidence** — reading docs alone is not evidence. You must execute commands and capture output.\n5. **Verify aggressively, escalate narrowly.** If an AC has 5 parts and you can verify 4, verify those 4 and escalate ONLY the specific part you cannot reach.\n6. **[ESCALATE] is ONLY for things that are genuinely impossible to automate** — physical hardware, paid external services, human visual judgment. Infrastructure problems are NOT valid escalation reasons.\n7. **Never switch to unit-testable verification.** If Docker verification doesn't work, report WHY as a [FAIL].\n\n## Verification Strategy for This Story\n\nThis story is about the verify-prompt template including observability check instructions, and the `codeharness verify` parser counting observability gaps. Here's how to verify each AC:\n\n**AC1 (template includes observability query):** Use the codeharness CLI to generate or inspect the verify prompt template output. The template should include a \"Step 3.5: Observability Check After Each Command\" section with the VictoriaLogs query. You can test this by running `docker exec codeharness-verify codeharness --help` to discover relevant commands, then exercise them.\n\n**AC2 (proof includes [OBSERVABILITY GAP] tag):** Create a mock proof document with the `[OBSERVABILITY GAP]` tag and feed it to the parser. Or verify the template instructs the verifier to include this tag.\n\n**AC3 (codeharness verify parses gaps separately):** Create a proof document with some gaps and some passes, then run `codeharness verify --story <test-key>` and check the output reports gaps separately from functional failures.\n\n**AC4 (runtime coverage = 70%):** The computation is 7/10 ACs with logs = 70%. This may be verifiable by running the runtime coverage computation through the CLI or by creating a test proof with specific gap patterns.\n\nIMPORTANT: Start by exploring what CLI commands are available (`codeharness --help`, `codeharness verify --help`) and what the README says. Then figure out how to exercise each AC.\n\n## Session Issues\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Problems encountered\n- Workarounds applied\n- Risks identified\n- Observations\nIf nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`","subagent_type":"general-purpose"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5288,"cache_read_input_tokens":48488,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":5288},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8712fecb-812b-48fe-bd95-ad6ae808447d","uuid":"084ecef4-75da-4a50-bb05-5503c90238f1"}
